    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">18. Fenchurch Street, | London. | E.C.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>11<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> October 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I have your letter telegram of yesterday.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>I think that the searches for incumbrances may be made,— and that the purchase may be completed, in three days,— say by the end of the present week.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I assume that the seller is respectable and that his statements are deemed <hi rend="underline">reliable</hi>. And it is, in my opinion, practically prudent not to insert any covenant for the production of title deeds, nor to make any alteration in the deed.</p>
<p>The declaration to tax dower of any widow of your Father is formal but correct.</p>
<p>The deed will, I hope, be sent to you ready for execution on Friday. And I will send with it instructions as to its formal execution &amp; attestation. I think that you will be able to do all that is requisite: but I shall be glad to send a clerk to obtain M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> S Sales execution &amp; to attest it,—at any time or place,—if you should prefer that course.</p>
<p>I have no title deeds here relating to your Fathers property.</p>
<p>I am | My dear Sir | Yours truly | W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi>. M Hacon</p> 
                    <p rend="left">L. Darwin Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>. | Brompton Barracks | Chatham</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">No telegram from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1230.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Leonard Darwin</ref> to Hacon has been found and Leonard denied having sent one (see <ref target="DCP-LETT-13395.xml">letter from Leonard Darwin, 12 October [1881]</ref>). They had been in communication about a possible land purchase by CD (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Hacon was handling CD’s purchase from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4149.xml">Sydney Sales</ref> of a strip of land adjacent to Down House (see <ref target="DCP-LETT-13379.xml">letter from W. M. Hacon to Leonard Darwin, 8 October 1881</ref>).</note>         
        </div>             
                 
